indicator.label: Aid
indicator.description: Most comparisons between donors are based only on how much aid each gives: in the the CDI, quantity is only half of the picture, because quality is also taken into account. The CDI uses the Quality of Official Development Assistance (QuODA) to assess the quality of donor’s aid programs. QuODA offers a comprehensive assessment of each donor’s development assistance by analyzing 31 indicators focusing on development impact, fostering institutions, reducing burden, and promoting transparency. The aid quality score for each country reflects the quality of its bilateral aid institutions, and the quality of the multilateral institutions through which it spends its aid.

indicator.label: official development assistance/GNI
indicator.description: Official development assistance countries report to the Development Assistance Committee of the OECD.
indicator.explanation: Official development assistance countries report to the Development Assistance Committee of the OECD. Sources: DAC online database.

indicator.label: Quality of Official Development Assistance
indicator.description: The CDI uses the Quality of Official Development Assistance (QuODA) to assess the quality of donor’s aid programs. QuODA offers a comprehensive assessment of each donor’s development assistance by analyzing 31 indicators focusing on development impact, fostering institutions, reducing burden, and promoting transparency. The aid quality score for each country reflects the quality of its bilateral aid institutions, and the quality of the multilateral institutions through which it spends its aid.
indicator.explanation: QuODA offers a comprehensive assessment of each donor’s development assistance by analyzing 31 indicators focusing on development impact, fostering institutions, reducing burden, and promoting transparency. The aid quality score for each country reflects the quality of its bilateral aid institutions, and the quality of the multilateral institutions through which it spends its aid. Source:

indicator.label: Trade
indicator.description: The trade component of the CDI penalizes countries for erecting barriers to imports of goods, such as crops and clothing, from developing countries, as well as services such as banking and freight hauling. Counted are tariffs (taxes) on imports, subsidies for domestic farmers, red tape and delays in processing imports, and legal restrictions on purchasing services from other countries.

indicator.label: Tariffs on clothing from developing countries
indicator.description: A tariff is like a sales tax or VAT on imports, and is measured here in the same way, as a percentage of the value of the goods taxed.
indicator.explanation: Ad valorem equivalent of duties on imports from developing countries. Underlying data by importer and exporter at the Harmonized System (HS) 6-digit level are from the Market Access Maps database of the Centre' de Centre d’Etudes Prospectives et d’Informations Internationales (CEPII). Definitions of major product categories such as rice and clothing come from version 6 of the Global Trade Analysis Project (GTAP) database. Tariffs are averaged within these categories using a methodology described in CGD Working Paper 66. "Corn" includes other minor grains. "Rice" is unprocess, paddy rice. "Sugar" is processed sugar, not sugar cane or beet.

indicator.label: Trade-distorting farm subsidies
indicator.description: When rich countries subsidize production from their own farmers and agricultural corporations, they grow more food, world food prices fall, and poor-country farmers suffer.
indicator.explanation: Government payments to farmers that affect incentives for production, averaged over the last three years with data and taken as a fraction of total agricultural production at farmgate prices. Excludes payments based on overall farm income as non-distorting and counts half of payments based on historical entitlements, as discussed in CGD Working Paper 66. Source: Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development, Producer and Consumer Support Estimates database .

indicator.label: Cost to import shipping container
indicator.description: Importing goods through ports requires paying fees (or bribes), completing paperwork, and waiting for inspection and approval. Some countries have streamlined these processes more than others.
indicator.explanation: World Bank, Doing Business survey.

indicator.label: Documents required to import
indicator.description: Importing goods through ports nécessite paying fees (or bribes), completing paperwork, and waiting for inspection and approval. Some countries have streamlined these processes more than others.
indicator.explanation: World Bank, Doing Business survey.

indicator.label: Days to import shipping container
indicator.description: Importing goods through ports requires paying fees (or bribes), completing paperwork, and waiting for inspection and approval. Some countries have streamlined these processes more than others.
indicator.explanation: World Bank, Doing Business survey.

indicator.label: Services Trade Restrictiveness Index
indicator.description: Most exports from developing countries are things: tangible objects such as phones and wheat. When a person in one country provides a service such as consulting or freight hauling to someone in another country, that too is trade, in services. Governments vary in how freely they allow imports of services.
indicator.explanation: The Services Trade Restrictiveness Index measures legal limitations on participation by foreigners in such serivce industries as law, retail banking, and insruance. Sources: <http://www.oecd.org/tad/services-trade/services-trade-restrictiveness-index.htm>

indicator.label: Finance
indicator.description: The finance component of the CDI compares rich countries on policies that encourage constructive investment in poor countries and transparency in financial transactions within their jurisdictions. For example, do governments support international efforts to ensure transparency in extractive industries investments? Do they offer insurance against political risks, such as expropriation, to encourage domestic companies to venture abroad? Do they have regulations in place to prevent tax evasion and reduce illicit financial flows out of developing countries?

indicator.label: Political risk insurance
indicator.description: Most rich-country governments offer insurance to their corporations investing overseas in case a foreign government seizes property of theirs, such as factories. Some check projects for environmental or labor abuses before backing them.
indicator.explanation: Indicator is based on a survey of government policies using a checklist approach. Questions for political risk insurance include: does the country have a national political risk insurance agency? Is the country a member of the Multilateral Investment Guarantee Agency ? Does the national agency screen for environmental, labor standards, and human rights issues? Designed by Theodore Moran; for more see Technical Paper .

indicator.label: Combating corruption
indicator.description: The CDI rewards countries that combat overseas bribery by their own corporations. For example, they may participate aggressively in the Extractive Industries Transparency Initiative, which presses oil, gas, and mining companies to publicly disclose all payments they make to developing country officials to obtain extraction rights.
indicator.explanation: Indicator is based on a survey of government policies using a checklist approach. Questions for the corruption indicator include: how has the country progressed in implementing the OECD Convention against Bribery of Foreign Public Officials in International Business Transactions? Has it participated in “publish what you pay” initiatives? Designed by Theodore Moran; for more see Technical Paper .

indicator.label: Other support for foreign investment
indicator.description: Other policies that promote investment include assistance to companies looking for overseas investment opportunities and a penalty for lobbying developing-country governments not to enforce labor and environmental rules for foreign factories.
indicator.explanation: Indicator is based on a survey of government policies using a checklist approach. Questions for this indicator include: does the country assist its firms in identifying investment opportunities? Does it advocate against receiving countries applying labor, environmental, or human rights standards to FDI ? Designed by Theodore Moran; for more see Technical Paper .

indicator.label: Facilitating portfolio investment
indicator.description: Some countries adopt policies that facilitate portfolio investment in developing countries--investing in their stock and bond markets. Other governments lose points for preventing pension funds from investing prudent fractions of their assets in developing countries.
indicator.explanation: Indicator is based on a survey of government policies using a checklist approach. Questions for the portfolio investment indicator include: Does it provide support for portfolio flows, for example by lending start-up capital to mutual funds investing in developing countries? Does the country eschew restrictions on portfolio investments in developing countries by home country pension funds? Designed by Theodore Moran; for more see Technical Paper .

indicator.label: Financial transparency
indicator.description: When governments permit secrecy in financial transactions within their jurisdiction, they facilitate illicit activities around the world, including corruption, tax evasion, and trafficking in guns, drugs, and people. The CDI rewards countries for policies that promote transparency in financial flows.
indicator.explanation: The <a href="http://www.financialsecrecyindex.com/" target="_new">Financial Secrecy Index</a.> of the Tax Justice Network assesses governments on policies in such areas as corporate transparency and efficiency of tax administration. Used here is the FSI "Secrecy Score," transformed to a 1-5 scale on which a higher number indicates more transparency.

indicator.label: Migration
indicator.description: The migration component of the CDI compares rich countries on how easy they make it for people from poor ones to immigrate, find work or get education, send home money--and even return home with new skills and capital.

indicator.label: Recorded inflow of developing-country migrants, recent year
indicator.description: Gross inflow of migrants from developing countries per year as a share of receiving country population. Figures come from immigration agencies and most likely miss illegal migrants. Immigration from poorer countries is rewarded more. Openness to migrants creates opportunities for them to earn more, send home money, get education, and return with new skills and capital.
indicator.explanation: Gross inflow of migrants from non-CDI countries in a recent year, taken as a fraction of receiving country population. Illegal immigrants are probably undercounted. To reward acceptance of immigrants from the poorest countries, inflow totals are discounted by the average poverty discount factor for the CDI indicator on change in number of unskilled residents from developing countries. Source: Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) International Migration Database.

indicator.label: Students from developing countries
indicator.description: Number of students from developing countries as a fraction of all foreign students.
indicator.explanation: Number of students from ODA eligible countries as a fraction of all foreign students. Source: Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) Online Education Database.

indicator.label: Refugees and asylum applications accepted
indicator.description: This indicator adds together the number of refugees living in a country and the number of asylum applications accepted in a recent year, all divided by the host country's gross domestic product.
indicator.explanation: Sums the resident stock of refugees and other "persons of concern" to the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), as well as asylum applications accepted in a recent year, all taken over host-country purchasing power parity GDP. Simplifies UNHCR's own index, using data from the UNHCR Statistical Yearbook .

indicator.label: Environment
indicator.description: The environment component of the CDI compares rich countries on policies that affect shared global resources such as the atmosphere and oceans. Rich countries use these resources disproportionately while poor ones are less equipped to adapt to the consequences, such as global warming. Countries do well if their greenhouse gas emissions are falling, if their gas taxes are high, if they do not subsidize the fishing industry, and if they control imports of illegally cut tropical timber.

indicator.label: Greenhouse gas emissions
indicator.description: Developing countries stand to bear the brunt of droughts and sea level rise from global warming, but rich countries cause more of the problem, per person.
indicator.explanation: Per-capita emissions of carbon dioxide (CO2) as well as methane (CH4), nitrous oxide (N2O), hydrofluorocarbons (HFCs), perfluorocarbons (PFCs), sulfur hexafluoride (SF6), all converted to CO2-equivalent tons based on relative warming potential. Includes emissions from burning coal, oil, and natural gas, as well as net emissions from land use and land use change, such as deforestation and afforestation. To these are added the CO2 equivalent of fossil fuel production. Fossil fuel production figures include production of oil, gas, and coal. Source: United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change.

indicator.label: Fossil fuel production
indicator.description: Developing countries stand to bear the brunt of droughts and sea level rise from global warming, but rich countries cause more of the problem, per person. While some rich countries emit large amounts of CO2, others export the problem by producing fossil fuels to be used by other countries.
indicator.explanation: Fossil fuel production figures include production of oil, gas, and coal. Source: <http://www.bp.com/content/dam/bp/pdf/statistical-review/statistical_review_of_world_energy_2013.pdf>.

indicator.label: Economic growth minus emissions growth
indicator.description: In the last ten years, some countries have restrained greenhouse gas emissions even as their economies have grown. In other countries, however, emissions have steadily increased along with GDP.
indicator.explanation: Average annual growth of the ratio between a country’s gross domestic product and its greenhouse gas emissions over the past 10 years. Growth rates calculated on “least squares” basis. Source: United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change and the World Bank.

indicator.label: Gasoline tax
indicator.description: Taxes on gasoline (petrol) encourage people to drive smaller cars and drive less, keeping global warming gases out of the air.
indicator.explanation: Total taxes on premium unleaded gasoline per liter, including sales taxes or value added tax (VAT), converted to dollars using purchasing power parities. Source: International Energy Agency .

indicator.label: Use of chemicals that damage the ozone layer
indicator.shortlabel: Use of chemicals that damage the ozone layer
indicator.description: Rich countries still consume some chemicals that damage the ozone layer, though far less than they once did, thanks to the internationally agreed Montreal Protocol.
indicator.explanation: Per-capita consumption of certain ozone-depleting chemicals, namely chlorofluorocarbons (CFCs), hydrochlorofluorocarbons (HCFCs), and methyl bromide. All converted to ozone-depleting-potential (ODP) tons based on relative damage potential. Source: United Nations Environment Programme, Ozone Secretariat .

indicator.label: Ratification of Kyoto Protocol on climate change
indicator.description: Though only a first step, the Kyoto Protocol is the international community's most serious attempt yet to slow global warming. A majority of signatories have ratified it, bringing it into force.
indicator.explanation: Whether a country has ratified the Kyoto Protocol to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change. Source: United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change.

indicator.label: Subsidies for fishing
indicator.description: Government subsidies to the fishing industry spur overfishing in international waters, including those off the coast of developing countries, depriving local fishers of livelihoods.
indicator.explanation: Per-capita government spending that specifically supports the fishing industry. Excludes general services, such as funding for the coast guard, fisheries management, membership in international organizations, and infrastructure construction.

indicator.label: Ratification of United Nations Fisheries Agreement
indicator.description: The U.N. fisheries agreement is the major international treaty that attempts to limit overfishing of the world's oceans.
indicator.explanation: Whether a country has signed the Agreement for the Implementation of the Provisions of the United Nations Convention on the Law of the Sea of December 10, 1982 relating to the Conservation and Management of Straddling Fish Stocks and Highly Migratory Fish Stocks. Source: United Nations, Division for Ocean Affairs and the Law of the Sea .

indicator.label: Biodiversity treaties participation
indicator.description: The four treaties considered here -- The Convention on Biological Diversity, The Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora, The Convention on Migratory Species, and Ramsar Convention on Wetlands -- are part of a global effort to preserve the diversity of life around the world. Countries' involvement in these treaties helps show the extent to which they are committed to this preservation effort.
indicator.explanation: Score is based on the timeliness of required reporting to the treaties, as well as how well the reports adhere to the reporting rules. Time frame: since 2001. Sources: Convention on Biological Diversity, Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora, Convention on Migratory Species, Ramsar Convention on Wetlands.

indicator.label: Imports of tropical timber
indicator.description: Perhaps no commodity import from developing countries is associated with as much environmental harm as tropical wood. Profits from logging, much of it illegal, typically accrue to the few while the costs are born by poor residents in and near the forests.
indicator.explanation: Per-capita imports, in dollar terms, of timber from tropical countries, defined as all goods in Harmonized System 2-digit codes 44 and 45 coming from non-CDI countries. All European nations assigned same, averaged, value since a few of these nations are the major ports of entry.Source: United Nations, Statistics Division, United Nations Commodity Trade Statistics (COMTRADE) Database.

indicator.label: Security
indicator.description: The security component of the CDI compares rich countries on military and related actions that affect developing countries. Rewarded are contributions to international peacekeeping and forcible humanitarian interventions that have an international mandate--unlike the invasion of Iraq but like the NATO intervention in Kosovo. Countries also get points for protecting sea lanes for global trade and participating in international security treaties such as the the Anti-Personnel Mine Ban Convention (Ottawa Treaty). It penalizes arms exports to authoritarian regimes with heavy military spending.

indicator.label: Contributions to U.N. peacekeeping budget
indicator.description: Funding for the United Nations Department of Peacekeeping Operations which runs several dozen operations around the world.
indicator.explanation: Dollar value of contributions to the budget of the U.N. Department of Peacekeeping Operations (UNDPKO). Contributions back to 1998 are counted through a weighted average, with weights discounted backward at 7%/year (50%/decade). Source: UNDPKO.

indicator.label: Personnel contributions to U.N. peacekeeping operations
indicator.description: Estimated cost of sending government troops, police, and other personnel to serve as "blue helmets" in U.N.-run peacekeeping.
indicator.explanation: Personnel contributions to U.N.-run operations are from UNDPKO. The estimated cost of these contributions is the sum of two components. The direct cost is $10,000/personnel/month, less the typical $1,000/month in reimbursement from the U.N., all converted to other currencies using purchasing power parities, Since these data are volatile, a weighted average is taken, back to 1993, using weights based on a discount rate of 7%/year (50%/decade). The indirect cost, meant to capture the long-run cost of training and maintaining troops so that they are available, is the portion of a country’s defense spending that can be allocated to those troops, based on the fraction they represent of all active-duty forces. The indirect cost is based on the peak annual contribution since 1993 after discounting backward at 7%/year. For more, see the CDI technical paper and the “Security data” sheet of the CDI spreadsheet.

indicator.label: Personnel contributions to non-U.N. peacekeeping and humanitarian interventions
indicator.description: Estimated cost of providing troops, police, and other personnel to non-U.N. peacekeeping operations and internationally endorsed military interventions, such as the 1999 U.N.-backed Australian intervention in East Timor.
indicator.explanation: Personnel contributions to non–U.N.-run operations are collected from the International Institute for Strategic Studies (IISS), The Military Balance, various years. Both peacekeeping and forcible humanitarian interventions are counted if they have an international mandate, such as from the U.N. Security Council or the NATO Council, are included. Costs are estimated as above, except leaving out the $1,000 reimbursement. For more, see the CDI technical paper and the “Security data” sheet of the CDI spreadsheet.

indicator.label: Positioning naval fleets near global trade routes
indicator.description: Estimated cost of maintaining and positioning naval fleets where they can protect sea lanes vital for international trade, such as in the Mediterranean Sea and Indian Ocean.
indicator.explanation: Source: Mark Stoker.

indicator.label: Arms exports to undemocratic, militaristic governments
indicator.description: Estimated value of arms exports to undemocratic, militaristic (high-defense-spending) countries. Exports to poorer countries weighted more.
indicator.explanation: Underlying pre-2006 data on bilateral transfers of major conventional weapon systems are from the Stockholm International Peace Research Institute (SIPRI) arms transfers database. Since the actual value of arms transfers is often not disclosed, or is subsidized, SIPRI assigns standard “trend indicator values,” such as $100 million for a certain class of fighter jet. Post-2006 data are collected directly from CDI government documents. Transfers are weighted by three factors reflecting recipient characteristics: the Voice and Accountability indicator of the World Bank’s Worldwide Governance Indicators; military spending as a fraction of GDP; and GDP per capita. The weighting only penalizes exports to countries below average on Voice and Accountability and above average on military spending, and the more so the poorer the recipient. Sales back to 1995 are counted through a weighted average, with weights discounted backward at 14%/year (50%/half-decade). Countries that do not disclose exports data receive a 0. For more, see the CDI technical paper and the “Security data” sheet of the CDI spreadsheet.

indicator.label: Ratification of security treaties
indicator.description: The proliferation of unconventional weapons—chemical, biological, radiological, nuclear—threatens the global economic order and the safety of citizens. Similarly, certain conventional weapons, such as land mines and cluster munitions, disproportionately impact civilians and vulnerable populations in poor countries. The CDI rewards countries for joining international weapons conventions intended to prevent the spread of these weapons, such as the (nuclear) Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT) and the Anti-Personnel Mine Ban Convention (Ottawa Treaty). A point is also awarded to countries that participate in the International Criminal Court (ICC).
indicator.explanation: Whether a country is a party to the International Criminal Court (ICC) and has ratified key unconventional and conventional weapons conventions. The latter includes the Non-Proliferation Treaty (NPT), the Comprehensive Nuclear-Test-Ban Treaty (CTBT), the Chemical Weapons Convention (CWC), the Biological Weapons Convention (BWC), the Anti-Personnel Mine Ban Convention (Ottawa Treaty), the Convention on Cluster Munitions (CCM), and the Convention on Certain Conventional Weapons (CCW). One point for each treaty ratified, with a maximum of 8. Sources: The Nuclear Threat Initiative, Ottawa Treaty, CCM, CCW, and ICC.

indicator.label: Technology
indicator.description: The technology component of the CDI analyses policies of the rich countries that support creation and dissemination of new technologies, which can profoundly shape life in developing countries. The component rewards government funding and tax breaks for research and development but penalizes certain patent and copyright rules deemed too restrictive to the flow of ideas across borders.

indicator.label: Government spending on R&D
indicator.description: When governments invest in research and development they can drive innovations in healthcare, communications, and other areas that benefit the entire world.
indicator.explanation: R&D spending data are from the Organisation for Economic Co-operation and Development (OECD) Government Budget Appropriations or Outlays for R&D database. Defense R&D is counted at 50% and industrial R&D at 75%.

indicator.label: Tax subsidy for private R&D
indicator.description: Governments can subsidize private research and development through the tax code. A country gets a zero on this measure if the government treats R&D spending as an ordinary expense for tax purposes. More favorable tax treatment earns a positive score.
indicator.explanation: Tax subsidy rates are simple averages of the rates for small and large companies. The benchmark is ordinary expensing, so that only tax treatment more favorable than expensing is considered a subsidy. Source: OECD Directorate for Science, Technology and Industry.

indicator.label: Restricts patenting of new plant and animal varieties
indicator.shortlabel: Restricts patenting of new plant and animal varieties
indicator.description: Some countries grant patents for plant and animal varieties developed through, for example, genetic engineering. Patent monopolies can deprive poor countries of access to such innovations, including ones that could be valuable for growing food.
indicator.explanation: Collected by Walter Park, American University. See the Technology Background paper.

indicator.label: Limits scope for patenting software innovations
indicator.shortlabel: Limits scope for patenting software innovations
indicator.description: Some countries allow patenting of software innovations, which inhibits access by developing countries.
indicator.explanation: Collected by Walter Park, American University. See the Technology Background paper.

indicator.label: Avoids intellectual property rights extension in bilateral trade treaties
indicator.shortlabel: Avoids intellectual property rights extension in bilateral trade treaties
indicator.description: Some rich countries, in negotiating trade treaties with individual developing countries, have leaned hard on them to extend protections for drug formulas and other intellectual property beyond international norms.
indicator.explanation: Collected by Walter Park, American University. See the Technology Background paper.

indicator.label: Permits technologies that break encryption systems and ease copying
indicator.shortlabel: Permits technologies that break encryption systems
indicator.description: Some countries have criminalized the development and use of technologies that can circumvent encryption devices and copy digital materials copyrighted in rich countries.
indicator.explanation: Collected by Walter Park, American University. See the Technology Background paper.

indicator.label: Restricts copyrighting of databases
indicator.description: Some governments allowing copyrighting of large databases, including ones with data collected at public expense, which can limit access for developing-country researchers.
indicator.explanation: Collected by Walter Park, American University. See the Technology Background paper.

indicator.label: Revokes unused patents
indicator.description: Some countries revoke a patent if the holder does not “work” it—implement or license it—within a certain period, in order make the innovation freely available to others.
indicator.explanation: Collected by Walter Park, American University. See the Technology Background paper.

indicator.label: Will force patent holders to license to meet pressing social needs
indicator.shortlabel: Will force patent holders to license to meet social needs
indicator.description: Some countries can force patent holders to allow use of their patents if it serves a pressing social need, such as a vaccine might in the face of an epidemic.
indicator.explanation: Collected by Walter Park, American University. See the Technology Background paper.

indicator.label: Allows patent applications to be challenged
indicator.shortlabel: Allows patent applications to be challenged
indicator.description: Some countries make it easier for patent applications to be challenged before they are officially approved. This discourages companies from claiming ownership over ideas more properly in the public domain.
indicator.explanation: Collected by Walter Park, American University. See the Technology Background paper.

indicator.label: Provides patent exceptions for research purposes
indicator.shortlabel: Provides patent exceptions for research purposes
indicator.description: Patent exceptions allow some companies such as generic drug manufacturers to develop lower cost versions of the patented product before the expiration of the patent, increasing access to such innovations in poor countries.
indicator.explanation: Collected by Walter Park, American University. See the Technology Background paper.
